,"Seal, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Seal, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Hall Place, Seal, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Seal, Kent, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Theobald","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German and English: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’ + <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’. The English surname represents a learned form, re-created from French <i>Théobald</i>. The usual medieval forms of the name in English and German were <i>Tebald</i> and <i>Tibalt</i> (Old French <i>Teobaud</i>, <i>Tibaut</i>). Compare   Dewald   and   Diebold  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dewald","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Diebold</i>, from Middle High German <i>Dietbold</i>, from Old High German <i>diot</i> ‘people, nation’ + <i>bald</i> ‘brave, strong’. As an American surname this is also an altered form of the cognate   Theobald  . Compare   Davolt  ,   Dawalt  ,   Daywalt  ,   Devault   3, and   Dewalt   1.","History: One of the first Dewalds in North America was Johannes Michael Dewald from Medard, a village in the Palatinate, Germany, who arrived at Philadelphia, PA, in 1738 on the ship <i>Glasgow</i>. He married Maria Barbara Schmidt and settled in Berks County, PA. His father's surname was <i>Theobald</i>. Michael's descendants also bear some other altered forms of the surname, including <i>Dewalt</i>, <i>Dawalt</i>, and <i>Davolt</i>. — One of the earliest immigrants who bore the original German surname <i>Dewald</i> was Henry alias He(i)nrich Dewald from the Palatinate, Germany, who arrived in PA in 1766. His descendants mainly bear altered forms of the surname, especially   Devault  ."]},{"name":"Tidball","meanings":["English (Somerset and Devon): variant of   Theobald  ."]},{"name":"Tebbs","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Northamptonshire): variant of <b>Tebb</b>, which is usually from a pet form of the Middle English male personal name <i>Tebbold</i> (see   Theobald  )."]},{"name":"Tipple","meanings":["English (Norfolk): from the medieval personal name <i>Tebald</i>, <i>Tibalt</i> (see   Theobald  ).","German: nickname for a simple person, from Low German <i>tippel</i> ‘point, corner’ (a reference to the pointed shape of a fool's cap).","German: from a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name, a pet form of   Dietrich  ."]},{"name":"Tibbs","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Tibb</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Tibbe</i>, which was used in the 13th century as both male (from <i>Tibald</i>, see   Theobald  ) and female name (a shortened form of <i>Tibot</i>, a pet form of <i>Isabel</i>, see   Tebbutt  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John Theobald I, Baron Theobald Of Seal was born about 1354, in Seal, Kent, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. John Theobald. He died about 1380, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28."},"et":{"Abt 1354–Abt 1380":"umbes 1354–umbes 1380","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1354–1380":"1354–1380","Abt 1354":"umbes 1354","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","Abt 1380":"umbes 1380","1380":"1380","1439":"1439","Seal, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Seal, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hall Place, Seal, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Seal, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1354–Abt 1380":"noin 1354–noin 1380","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1354–1380":"1354